r races in a larger metropolitan area corresponds with greater racial intolerance, particularly for America’s white majority. But when whites, blacks, Latinos, and Asian Americans actually live in integrated neighborhoods, they feel less racial resentment. Paradoxically, this racial tolerance is usually also accompanied by feeling less connected to their community; it is no longer "theirs." Basing its findings on our most advanced means of gauging the impact of social environments on racial attitudes, The Paradoxes of Integration sensitively explores the benefits and at times, heavily borne, costs of integration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEthnic neighborhoodsxUnited States. 0aEthnic neighborhoodszUnited States. 0aMinoritiesxAttitudesxUnited States. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aSocial integrationxUnited States. 0aSocial integrationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aparadox, racism, racial, area, geography, ethnicity, american, united states, usa, daily life, change, progress, integrated, metropolitan, urban, city, metro, attitude, bias, society, social, culture, cultural, behavior, interpersonal, intolerance, tolerance, white, resentment, latino, asian, public, self sorting, multiculturalism, black.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226626642423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226626642/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles